● **Gross Domestic Product (GDP)** is the key indicator used to measure a country’s annual economic growth and overall economic size. The **“base year”** serves as the reference point for these calculations. Currently, **2011-12** is the base year, meaning GDP growth in subsequent years is measured against it. The government has now decided to adopt **2022-23 as the new base year,** with the revised data series scheduled for release on **February 27, 2026.** The revision aims to reflect the structural transformation of the economy by integrating new data sources such as **GST records** and the **Vahan** **vehicle registration portal**, while also refining methodologies to better capture emerging industries and the informal sector.
● The Ministry of Statistics & Programme Implementation carried out its **first Forward-Looking Survey** **on Private Corporate Sector CAPEX Investment Intentions** between **November 2024 and** **January 2025** and has published the findings. It also undertook a **Pilot Study on the Annual Survey** **of Services Sector Enterprises (ASSSE)** to gather insights on the incorporated service sector. However, a decision regarding the conduct of the **8th Economic Census** is yet to be finalised. **Therefore, option (b) is the correct answer.**
**Knowledge Box**
**Purpose of Revising the Base Year:**
● The main objective of revising the GDP base year is to **enhance the accuracy of** **economic measurement**. Updated and precise GDP estimates are crucial for **effective policy-making, informed business decisions and comprehensive** **economic analysis**. **The base year of national accounts has been revised on seven different occasions:**
● From 1948-49 to 1960-61 in August 1967;
● From 1960-61 to 1970-71 in January 1978;
● From 1970-71 to 1980-81 in February 1988;
● From 1980-81 to 1993-94 in February 1999;
● From 1993-94 to 1999-2000 in January 2006;
● From 1999-2000 to 2004-05 in January 2010; and
● From 2004-05 to 2011-12 on January 30, 2015.
